Introduction

To measure my progress and commitment to this course, I used this project to demonstrate how well I understood the objectives. The purpose of this work is to analyze and understand the trends and factors influencing population growth rates across various cities globally. This portfolio includes a comprehensive examination of simple and multiple linear regression models, as well as logistic regression for classification, to predict and analyze population growth rates. This enables me to experiment with and evaluate my understanding of the course objective

Project Motivation

In a rapidly urbanizing world, understanding the dynamics of population growth in cities is crucial for planning and policy-making. Population growth affects various aspects of urban life, including infrastructure, economy, environment, and social services. By analyzing the growth rates of cities, we can gain insights into trends and patterns that help in making informed decisions for sustainable development. This motivation was sure to solve a real world problem, which pushed me to apply the skills acquired to investigate.

Import the data set

In this section, I learned how to import a CSV file in R and use it for analysis. The data provides information on the population and growth rates of various cities around the world for 2024.

world_population_growth_rate_data <- read_csv("World population growth rate by cities 2024.csv")
data <- world_population_growth_rate_data

Data Dictionary n my quest to improve using R, I learned how to represent my data in my output file as a data dictionary. In this section, the data dictionary has been used to describe the data used in this work.

# Create the initial data dictionary manually
data_dictionary <- data.frame(
  Variable_Name = c("City", "Country", "Continent", "Population (2024)", "Population (2023)", "Growth Rate"),
  Data_Type = c("String", "String", "String", "Integer", "Integer", "Float"),

Basic Statistics of the Data

  • The data set includes 801 cities.
  • The mean population for 2024 is approximately 2.65 million, with a standard deviation of around 3.72 million.
  • The growth rate ranges from -0.0249 to 0.0582, with a mean of 0.0201.
  • The Continent explanatory variable is missing 11 data points. This issue will be addressed

Visusalizing the Missigness of the data

data |>
  
  gg_miss_var(show_pct = TRUE) +
  
  labs(title = "Missingness of World population growth rate by cities 2024 ") +
  
  ggthemes::theme_few()

The missingness graph indicates that the missing data points account for less than 1.5% of the total. This percentage is considered insignificant, so these rows will be excluded from the analysis.

# Remove rows where the continent is NA and standardize "Oceana" to "Oceania"
data <- data %>%
  filter(!is.na(Continent)) %>%
  mutate(Continent = ifelse(Continent == "Oceana", "Oceania", Continent))

# Check the unique entries to verify the changes
unique_continents <- unique(data$Continent)

Initial Analysis

Correlation Analysis

In this section, Correlation Analysis is performed to further understand the data

# Calculate the correlation matrix
correlation_matrix <- cor(world_population_growth_rate_data[, c("Population (2024)", "Population (2023)", "Growth Rate")])

# Melt the correlation matrix into long format
melted_correlation_matrix <- melt(correlation_matrix)

# Plot the correlation matrix
ggplot(data = melted_correlation_matrix, aes(x = Var1, y = Var2, fill = value)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white") +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "blue", high = "red", mid = "white", midpoint = 0, limit = c(-1, 1), space = "Lab", 
                       name = "Correlation") +
  theme_minimal() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, vjust = 1, size = 12, hjust = 1)) +
  coord_fixed() +
  geom_text(aes(label = round(value, 2)), color = "black", size = 4) + # Add correlation scores
  ggtitle("Correlation Matrix") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Correlation Analysis Insights

The correlation matrix reveals the following:

  • There is a perfect correlation (1.0) between the population in 2023 and 2024. This is expected because the 2024 population is derived from the 2023 population and the growth rate.
    • Interpretation: The population numbers for 2023 and 2024 are directly linked, so its no surprise they match up perfectly in our analysis.
  • The growth rate has a weak negative correlation with both the 2023 and 2024 populations (approximately -0.05).
    • Interpretation: Theres a very slight tendency for cities with larger populations to have slightly lower growth rates, but this relationship is very weak.

Growth Rate Analysis by Continent

In this section we investigate how Growth rates vary across different continents.

Variation in Growth Rate

Growth Rate Analysis by Continent Insights

  • Africa has the highest variability in growth rates, with several cities experiencing significantly higher growth rates compared to other continents.
    Interpretation: This means that while some cities in Africa are growing very rapidly, others might be growing more slowly.

  • Asia also shows relatively high growth rates, but with less variability compared to Africa.
    Interpretation: Many cities in Asia are growing steadily, though not as unevenly as in Africa.

  • Europe shows the lowest growth rates, with many cities experiencing minimal or even negative growth.
    Interpretation: Europes population growth is generally slower, with some cities possibly even shrinking.

Statistical Modelling

During this course, I have learned to apply statistical models to real-world data, aligning with the course objectives.

Simple Linear Regression

In this section, I started with linear regression to model the relationship between population size and growth rate. Specifically, we will develop a simple linear regression model where the dependent variable is the Growth Rate, and the independent variable is the Population (2023) of each city.

# Data preparation: transform the yearly population data
data$Log_Population_2023 <- log(data$`Population (2023)`)
data$Log_Population_2024 <- log(data$`Population (2024)`)

# Develop a simple linear regression model
model <- lm(`Growth Rate` ~ `Population (2023)`, data = data)

# Summarize the model
summary(model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = `Growth Rate` ~ `Population (2023)`, data = data)
## 
## Residuals:
##       Min        1Q    Median        3Q       Max 
## -0.043963 -0.007665 -0.000211  0.006527  0.037863 
## 
## Coefficients:

## (Intercept)          2.056e-02  5.295e-04  38.824   <2e-16 ***
## `Population (2023)` -1.839e-10  1.173e-10  -1.568    0.117    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
##

## F-statistic: 2.458 on 1 and 788 DF,  p-value: 0.1173
tidy_model <- tidy(model)

## # A tibble: 2  5

##   <chr>                   <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>

## 2 `Population (2023)` -1.84e-10  1.17e-10     -1.57 1.17e-  1
# Predict growth rates using the model
predictions <- predict(model, newdata = data)

Simple Linear Model Evaluation

  • Mean Squared Error (MSE): 0.01213
  • R-squared (R): 0.00311

The very low R value indicates that the simple linear regression model explains only about 0.31% of the variance in the growth rate. This suggests that the 2023 population alone is not a strong predictor of the growth rate.

# Plot the relationship and regression line

Lets add more explanatory variables and predict the growth rate using multiple regression.

Multiple Linear Regression

In this section, we will develop a multiple linear regression model to predict the growth rate of cities. The dependent variable in this model is the Growth Rate, and the independent variables include Population (2023), Population (2024), Continent, and Country. We aims to provide a more comprehensive understanding of the factors influencing city growth rates and to predict future growth rates.

# Convert categorical variables to factors
data$Continent <- as.factor(data$Continent)
data$Country <- as.factor(data$Country)

# Data preparation: create additional variables if needed
data$Log_Population_2023 <- log(data$`Population (2023)`)
data$Log_Population_2024 <- log(data$`Population (2024)`)
# Develop a multiple linear regression model
multiple_model <- lm(`Growth Rate` ~ `Population (2023)` + `Population (2024)` + Continent + Country, data = data)

# Summarize the model
summary(multiple_model)

Mutiple Linear Regression Model Evaluation

  • Mean Squared Error (MSE): 0.005358
  • R-squared (R): 0.8374

The R value of approximately 0.8374 indicates that the multiple linear regression model explains about 83.78% of the variance in the growth rate. This is a significant improvement over the simple linear regression model, which only explained about 0.31% of the variance. This high R value suggests that the multiple regression model is much more effective in capturing the relationship between the predictors (Population in 2023, Population in 2024, Continent, and Country) and the growth rate.

Predicted Growth Rates

From the predictions table:

Highest Predicted Growth Rates

  • Bujumbura from Africa (Burundi) is predicted to have the highest growth rate of 0.0582.
  • Kinshasa from Africa (DR Congo) follows closely behind.

Lowest Predicted Growth Rates

  • Bucharest in Romania (Europe) is predicted to have the lowest growth rate.
  • Beirut in Lebanon (Asia) has the second-lowest predicted growth rate.

These predictions align with our initial analysis, which identified significant variability in growth rates across different continents and countries. The high R value and the accurate predictions for both the highest and lowest growth rates indicate that the multiple regression model is better than the linear regression for predicting the growth rates of cities.

Logistic Regression

First created a threshold for the low and high using the mediam of growth rate to turn the regression problem to classification problem. This was initiated to predict cities with low or high growth rate

# Create a binary target variable based on the median growth rate
median_growth_rate <- median(data$`Growth Rate`)
data$Growth_Category <- ifelse(data$`Growth Rate` > median_growth_rate, 1, 0)

# Convert categorical variables to factors
data$Continent <- as.factor(data$Continent)
data$Country <- as.factor(data$Country)

# Step 2: Feature Selection
# Select relevant features for the classification model
features <- c("Population (2023)", "Population (2024)", "Continent", "Country")
df <- data[, c(features, "Growth_Category")]

# Step 3: Model Development
# Split the data into training and testing sets
set.seed(123)  # For reproducibility
split <- sample.split(df$Growth_Category, SplitRatio = 0.8)
training_set <- subset(df, split == TRUE)
testing_set <- subset(df, split == FALSE)

# Ensure the levels of the factor variables in the test set match those in the training set
training_set$Continent <- factor(training_set$Continent)
training_set$Country <- factor(training_set$Country)
testing_set$Continent <- factor(testing_set$Continent, levels = levels(training_set$Continent))
testing_set$Country <- factor(testing_set$Country, levels = levels(training_set$Country))

# Drop rows in the testing set that contain new levels
testing_set <- testing_set[!is.na(testing_set$Continent) & !is.na(testing_set$Country), ]

# Develop and fit the logistic regression model
logistic_model <- glm(Growth_Category ~ ., data = training_set, family = binomial)

# Step 4: Model Evaluation
# Predict the probabilities on the testing set
probabilities <- predict(logistic_model, newdata = testing_set, type = "response")

# Convert probabilities to binary predictions
predictions <- ifelse(probabilities > 0.5, 1, 0)

# Calculate accuracy, precision, recall, and F1 score
accuracy <- sum(predictions == testing_set$Growth_Category) / nrow(testing_set)
precision <- sum(predictions == 1 & testing_set$Growth_Category == 1) / sum(predictions == 1)
recall <- sum(predictions == 1 & testing_set$Growth_Category == 1) / sum(testing_set$Growth_Category == 1)
f1 <- 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall)

# Calculate ROC-AUC
pred <- prediction(probabilities, testing_set$Growth_Category)
perf <- performance(pred, "tpr", "fpr")
auc <- performance(pred, measure = "auc")
roc_auc <- auc@y.values[[1]]

# Print the evaluation metrics
print(paste("Accuracy:", round(accuracy, 3)))
## [1] "Accuracy: 0.883"
print(paste("Precision:", round(precision, 3)))
## [1] "Precision: 0.877"
print(paste("Recall:", round(recall, 3)))
## [1] "Recall: 0.889"
print(paste("F1 Score:", round(f1, 3)))
## [1] "F1 Score: 0.883"
print(paste("ROC-AUC:", round(roc_auc, 3)))
## [1] "ROC-AUC: 0.882"
# Plot ROC curve with evaluation metrics
plot(perf, col = "blue", lwd = 2, main = "ROC Curve")
abline(a = 0, b = 1, lty = 2, col = "red")
text(0.6, 0.4, paste("Accuracy:", round(accuracy, 3)), pos = 4)
text(0.6, 0.35, paste("Precision:", round(precision, 3)), pos = 4)
text(0.6, 0.3, paste("Recall:", round(recall, 3)), pos = 4)
text(0.6, 0.25, paste("F1 Score:", round(f1, 3)), pos = 4)
text(0.6, 0.2, paste("ROC-AUC:", round(roc_auc, 3)), pos = 4)

# Print the summary of the logistic regression model
summary(logistic_model)

Model Summary and Evaluation Metrics (Logistic Regression)

  • Accuracy: 0.883
    This metric indicates that the model correctly predicts the growth category of cities 88.3% of the time.

  • Precision: 0.877
    87.7% of the predictions that the growth rate is high are accurate.

  • Recall: 0.889
    The model correctly identifies 88.9% of the high-growth cities.

  • F1 Score: 0.883
    An F1 score of 0.883 indicates a good balance between precision and recall.

  • ROC-AUC: 0.882
    An AUC of 0.882 indicates a high level of discrimination between the growth categories. The models performance in distinguishing between high-growth and low-growth cities.

Key Findings

  • High Variability in Growth Rates Across Continents: Africa shows the highest variability in growth rates, indicating diverse growth patterns among its cities.

  • Significance of Multiple Factors: The multiple regression model, with an R of approximately 0.8374, demonstrates that a combination of factors (Population in 2023, Population in 2024, Continent, and Country) provides a better prediction of growth rates compared to a single factor.

  • Logistic Regression Performance: The logistic regression model effectively categorizes cities into high and low growth categories with high accuracy, precision, recall, and ROC-AUC, indicating its reliability in classification tasks.
